      <body>
			<div type="edition">
				<ab>
					<lb n="1"/>
					<unclear><g type="siddham"/></unclear>
						<g type="danda">.</g><g type="danda">.</g> tdaṃḥ ḅaṁḥ O hi suriyavikrama ḅaṁḥ sniḥ ṅa
					su rla
					piṁ
					ṅa ta kiṁ kha O <unclear>sn</unclear>iḥ sniḥ tru rla
					plaṁ
					tiṁ tdaṃḥ ḅaṁḥ O ru kleḥ yaṁ </ab>
				<!-- AG2MM3: please make adjustments re @with, which should here always be @source, I suppose (but you should check). No need any other readings by Blagden than those published in 1913-14. This applies to all urns. Please also check for conformity with the instructions representation of readings identical to ours or identical variant readings offered by different authorities. Won't remark on this in next files at this stage, until we have reached consensus on how to tag the editions, and I can focus on correcting departures from our system. -->
				<!-- MM2AG: in 003, you treated Blagden1913-14 as @resp but here as @source. Will unify once I know which attribute is best. -->
				<!-- MM2AG: <rdg source="Blagden" source="PR"> for a case of identical readings was red-flagged by oXygen for having more than one of the same attribute, so for now I have retained my earlier redundant style of tagging. -->
			</div>
			<div type="apparatus">
				<listApp>
					<app loc="1">
						<!-- MM2AG: should this note be dropped since we no longer read 'five' with m-? -->
						<lem>miṁ</lem>
						<note>Comparison of &lt;miṁ&gt; and &lt;plaṁ&gt; in this inscription versus &lt;ma&gt; in PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00003">3</ref> seems to support the &lt;m&gt; reading. See images in corresponding Word file. But accidental damage to an original &lt;p&gt;, creating the misleading impression of presence of a crossbar typical of &lt;m&gt;, can plausibly be
							postulated should a &lt;p&gt; be required. If the phrase &lt;rla miṁ ṅa&gt; does mean ‘months five’, then &lt;p&gt; is etymologically more likely for the pre-syllable associated with ‘five’ (&lt;ṅa&gt;): cf. Lushai panga (Matisoff, HPTB, p. 149). <!-- AG2MM: HPTB presumably to be added to our general bibliography. -->
						</note>
					</app>
				<app loc="1">
						<lem>suriyavikrama</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">sūriyavikrama</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">sūriyavikrama</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>ṅa</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(ṅ)a</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">(ṅa)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>su rla</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">sū (de)</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">sū (de)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>piṁ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(p)iṁ</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">(pi)ṁ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>ṅa</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(ṅ)a</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>kiṁ kha</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(k)iṁ (kha)</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">(kiṁ) (kha)</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem><unclear>sn</unclear>iḥ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">[sn]iḥ</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">sniḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>tru rla</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">t[ru sau]</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">tru sau</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>plaṁ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">p(ḷ)aṁ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>tiṁ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">tiḥ</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:ThaMyat1963_01">tiḥ</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>kleḥ</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01">(kḷ)eḥ</rdg>
					</app></listApp>
			</div>
			<div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				<p>Blagden:</p>
				<ab>Year 50 (688 AD), 5th month, Sūriyavikrama himself died, aged 64 years.</ab>
				<p>San Win (2003: 18), revises Blagden as:</p>
				<ab>In the year 64 King Sūriya Vikrama died, at the age of 50 years and 5 months.</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="commentary">
				<p><!-- commentary --></p>
			</div>
			<div type="bibliography">
				<!--ASI 1912-13, pt. I, 29. — ASB 1913, 13-4. — Blagden 1913-14 (C). — PR, 47 (C), 51. — PPPB I, 48, 57 n. 13, 126-7.-->
				<!--[Todo: markup citedRange elements if necessary]-->
				<p><bibl><ptr target="bib:ASI"/><citedRange>1912-13: pt. I, 29</citedRange></bibl>, discusses the four Sriksetra urn inscriptions (PYU <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00003">3</ref>, <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00004">4</ref>, <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00005">5</ref> and <ref target="DHARMA_INSPYU00006">6</ref>) with reference to Blagden’s dating. <bibl><ptr target="bib:ASB"/><citedRange>1913:  13-4</citedRange></bibl> cites Blagden’s reading of the names Sūriyavikrama. <bibl><ptr target="bib:Blagden1913-1914_01"/><citedRange>(C)</citedRange></bibl> provides a transliteration of the inscription and tentative translation. <bibl><ptr target="bib:ThaMyat1963_01"/><citedRange>47 (C), 51</citedRange></bibl>, has an eye drawing, a Burmese transliteration and an English translation (that matches Blagden’s). Luce, <bibl><ptr target="bib:Luce1985_01"/><citedRange>I, 48, 57 n. 13, 126-7</citedRange></bibl>, cites earlier works and repeats Blagden’s translation. Recently, <bibl><ptr target="bib:SeinWin2016_01"/><citedRange>61, 64</citedRange></bibl> published a slightly modified transliteration (in Burmese script) and a glossary. Re-edited here from published photographs.</p>
